{"title_page": "Fetal hemoglobin", "text_new": "{{Infobox heteropolypeptide\n | heteropolymer = Fetal hemoglobin \n | polymer_type = 4 subunits, \u03b1<sub>2</sub>\u03b3<sub>2</sub>\n | protein_type = [[metalloprotein]], [[globulin]]\n | function = [[oxygen]]-transport\n | cofactors = [[heme]] (4)\n | image = Structure of Fetal Hemoglobin (HbF).png\n | image_source = Structure of Fetal Hemoglobin (HbF). The '''2\u03b1''' and '''2\u03b3''' subunits are in red and yellow, respectively, and the iron-containing [[heme]] groups in green. From {{PDB|4MQJ}}, by authors Soman, J. and Olson J.S.\n | SubunitCount = 4\n | subunit1 = Hb-\u03b11\n | gene1 = [[HBA1]]\n | locus1 = [[Chromosome 16|Chr. 16]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBA1#location?chromosome=16p13.3 p13.3]\n | subunit2 = Hb-\u03b12\n | gene2 = [[HBA2]]\n | locus2 = [[Chromosome 16|Chr. 16]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBA2#location?chromosome=16p13.3 p13.3]\n | subunit3 = Hb-\u03b31\n | gene3 = [[HBG1]]\n | locus3 = [[Chromosome 11|Chr. 11]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG1#location?chromosome=11p15.4 p15.4]\n | subunit4 = Hb-\u03b32\n | gene4 = [[HBG2]]\n | locus4 = [[Chromosome 11|Chr. 11]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG2#location?chromosome=11p15.4 p15.4]\n}}\n\n'''Fetal hemoglobin''', or '''foetal haemoglobin''' (also '''hemoglobin F''', '''HbF''', or '''\u03b1<sub>2</sub>\u03b3<sub>2</sub>''') is the main [[oxygen]] [[transport protein|carrier protein]] in the human [[fetus]]. Hemoglobin F is found in fetal red blood cells and it is involved in transporting oxygen from the mother's [[bloodstream]] to organs and tissues in the fetus. It is produced at around 6 weeks of pregnancy <ref name=\"David 1998\">{{cite book |last= Linch|first= David|date= 1998|title= Encyclopedia of Immunology (second edition)|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B0122267656001031 |publisher= Elsevier|isbn= 978-0-12-226765-9}}</ref> and the levels remain high after birth until the baby is roughly 2-4 months old.<ref name=\"Schechter2008\">{{Cite journal | author=Schechter A | title=Hemoglobin research and the origins of molecular medicine | journal=[[Blood]] | volume=112(10) | year=2008 | pages=3927\u20133938 | doi=10.1182/blood-2008-04-078188 }}</ref> Hemoglobin F has a different composition from the adult forms of [[hemoglobin]], which allows it to bind (or attach to) oxygen more strongly. This way, the developing fetus is able to retrieve oxygen from the mother's bloodstream, which occurs through the [[placenta]] found in the mother\u2019s [[uterus]].<ref name=\"Wang Y & Zhao S\">{{Cite book | authors= Wang Y, Zhao S| title= Vascular Biology of the Placenta| year=2010 | chapter=Chapter 2: Placental Blood Circulation | publisher=Morgan & Claypool Life Sciences }}</ref>\n\n\nIn the newborn, levels of hemoglobin F gradually decrease and reach adult levels (less than 1% of total hemoglobin) usually within 1 year of life, as adult forms of hemoglobin begin to be produced.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\">{{cite book |last= Wild|first= Barbara|date= 2017|title= Dacie and Lewis Practical Haematology (twelfth edition)|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B978070206696200014X |publisher= Elsevier|isbn= 978-0-7020-6696-2}}</ref> Diseases such as [[\u03b2-thalassemia]], which affect components of the adult hemoglobin, can delay this switch and cause hemoglobin F levels to be higher than normal in these patients.<ref name=\"Orapan2016\">{{Cite journal | author=Orapan S & Suthat F| title=Fetal hemoglobin regulation in \u03b2-thalassemia: heterogeneity, modifiers and therapeutic approaches | journal=[[Expert review of hematology]] | volume=9(12) |year=2016 | pages=1129\u20131137 | doi=10.1080/17474086.2016.1255142 }}</ref> In sickle cell anaemia, increasing the production of hemoglobin F has been used as a treatment, as it relieves some of the symptoms of the disease.<ref name=\"pmid18458272\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Lanzkron S, Strouse JJ, Wilson R, etal |title=Systematic review: Hydroxyurea for the treatment of adults with sickle cell disease |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |volume=148 |issue=12 |pages=939\u201355 |date=June 2008 |pmid=18458272 |doi= 10.7326/0003-4819-148-12-200806170-00221|url= |pmc=3256736}}</ref>\n\n\n==Structure and genetics==\nHemoglobin F, like hemoglobin forms found in adults ([[hemoglobin A]] and [[hemoglobin A2]]), have four [[protein subunit|subunits]] or chains. Each subunit contains a [[heme]] group with an iron element which is key in allowing the binding and unbinding of oxygen. As hemoglobin F has 4 heme groups, it can bind to up to four oxygen molecules.<ref name=brsphys>{{cite book |author=Costanzo, Linda S. |title=Physiology |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location=Hagerstwon, MD |year=2007 |isbn=978-0781773119 |url=https://archive.org/details/physiology00cost_0 }}</ref> It is composed of '''two \u03b1 (alpha)''' subunits and '''two \u03b3 (gamma)''' subunits, whereas hemoglobin A (97% of total hemoglobin in adults) is composed of two \u03b1 and two \u03b2 (beta) subunits.\n\nIn humans, the \u03b1 subunit is encoded on [[chromosome 16 (human)|chromosome 16]] and the \u03b3 subunit is encoded on [[chromosome 11 (human)|chromosome 11]]. There are 2 very similar [[gene]]s that code for the \u03b1 subunit, [[HBA1]] and [[HBA2]]. The protein that they produce is identical, but they differ in gene regulatory regions that determine when or how much of the protein is produced. This leads to HBA1 and HBA2 each contributing with 40% and 60%, respectively, of the total of \u03b1 subunits produced. As a consequence, mutations on the HBA2 gene are expected to have a stronger effect than mutations on the HBA1 gene.<ref name=\"Samaneh2018\">{{Cite journal | author=Samaneh F & Cornelis L| title=Molecular basis of \u03b1-thalassemia | journal=[[Blood cells, Molecules and Diseases]] | volume=70 |year=2018 | pages=43\u201353 | doi=10.1016/j.bcmd.2017.09.004 }}</ref> \nThere are also two similar copies of the gene coding for the \u03b3 subunit, HBG1 and HBG2, but the protein produced is slightly different, just in one [[amino acid|protein unit]]: HBG1 codes for the protein form with an [[alanine]] at position 136, whereas HBG2 codes for a [[glycine]] (see [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG1|NIH]).\n\n==When hemoglobin F is produced==\n[[File:Postnatal genetics en.svg|thumb|300px|[[Gene expression]] of hemoglobin before and after birth, also showing the cells types and organs where different subunits are being produced over time (data on ''Wood W.G.'', (1976). '''Br. Med. Bull. 32, 282.''') Figure last adapted by user Leonid 2.]]\n\nDuring the first 3 months of pregnancy, the main form of hemoglobin in the fetus is [[embryonic hemoglobin]], which has 3 variants. The production of fetal hemoglobin starts from week 6, but it's only from 3 months onwards that it becomes the main type found in red blood cells.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\"/>\nThe switch to produce adult forms of hemoglobin (especially Hemoglobin A) starts at around 40 weeks of gestation, which is close to the expected time of birth.<ref name=\"David 1998\"/> At birth, hemoglobin F comprises 50-95% of the infant's hemoglobin and at around 6 months after birth, hemoglobin A becomes the predominant type. By the time the baby is one year old, the proportions of different types of hemoglobin are expected to approximate the adult levels.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\" />\n\nIn healthy adults, the composition of hemoglobin is hemoglobin A (~97%), hemoglobin A2 (2.2 - 3.5%) and hemoglobin F (<1%).<ref name=\"Caroline 2012\">{{Cite journal | author=Caroline T & Andrew L| title= Physiology of haemoglobin| journal=[[Continuing Education in Anaesthesia Critical Care & Pain]] | volume=12(5) |year=2012 | pages=251\u2013256 | doi=10.1093/bjaceaccp/mks025 }}</ref>\n\nCertain genetic abnormalities can cause the switch to adult hemoglobin synthesis to fail, resulting in a condition known as [[hereditary persistence of fetal hemoglobin]] (HPFH).\n\n\n\n==Binding to oxygen==\n===Why hemoglobin F has higher oxygen affinity===\nThe 4 hemes, which are the oxygen-binding parts of hemoglobin, are similar between hemoglobin F and other types of hemoglobin, including hemoglobin A. Thus, the key feature that allows hemoglobin F to bind more strongly to oxygen is by having \u03b3 subunits (instead of \u03b2, for example). In fact, some naturally existing molecules in our body can bind to hemoglobin and change its binding affinity for oxygen. One of the molecules is [[2,3-bisphosphoglycerate|2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG)]] and it enhances hemoglobin\u2019s ability to release oxygen.<ref name=\"Gerald 2018\">  {{Cite book | authors= Litwack G| title= Human Biochemistry | year=2018 | chapter=Chapter 8 \u2013 Glycolysis and Glocuneogenesis | publisher=Academic press| isbn = 978-0-12-383864-3}} </ref> 2,3-BPG interacts much more with hemoglobin A than hemoglobin F. This is because the adult \u03b2 subunit has more positive charges than the fetal \u03b3 subunit, which attract the negative charges from 2,3-BPG. Due to the preference of 2,3-BPG for hemoglobin A, hemoglobin F binds to oxygen with more affinity, in average.<ref name=\"Duane 2016\"> {{cite web |url=https://biosci.mcdb.ucsb.edu/biochemistry/tw-hbn/hbf/hbf-overview.htm\n|title= Comparing the molecular structure differences between HbF and HbA that affect BPG binding|last= Sears|first= Duane|date= 2016|website= https://biosci.mcdb.ucsb.edu/|publisher= Biosci Portal |access-date= 11 March 2020}} </ref>\n\n===Quantification of oxygen binding=== \nTo quantify how strongly a certain type of hemoglobin binds to oxygen (or its affinity for oxygen), a parameter called P50 is often used. In a given situation, P50 can be understood as the minimum concentration of oxygen needed for 50% of the hemoglobin molecules to bind to it.<ref name=\"Vibhu2006\">  {{Cite book | authors= Awasthi V, Goins E and Phillips W| title= Blood Substitutes| year=2006 | chapter=Chapter 43 \u2013 Liposome-encapsulated hemoglobin: history, preparation and evaluation | publisher=Academic press| isbn = 978-0-12-759760-7}} </ref> For example, Hemoglobin F has a lower P50 than hemoglobin A. This means that if we have the same amount of hemoglobin F and hemoglobin A in the blood and add oxygen to it, half of hemoglobin F will bind to oxygen before half of hemoglobin A manages to do so. Therefore, a lower P50 means stronger binding or higher affinity for oxygen. \n\nFor reference, the P50 of fetal hemoglobin is roughly 19 mmHg (a measure of pressure), whereas adult hemoglobin is approximately 26.8 mmHg (see [[Blood gas tension]]).<ref name=\"Yacov2017\">  {{Cite book | authors= Yacov R, Derek K and Namasivayam A| title= Assisted Ventilation of the Neonate (sixth edition)| year=2017 | chapter=Chapter 10 \u2013 Blood gases: technical aspects and interpretation | publisher=Elsevier| isbn = 978-0-323-39006-4 }} </ref>\n\n\n==Oxygen exchange in the womb==\nDuring pregnancy, the mother\u2019s circulatory system delivers oxygen and nutrients to the fetus and carries away nutrient-depleted blood enriched with carbon dioxide. The maternal and fetal-placental circulation are separate and the exchange of molecules occurs in a region between maternal and fetal blood vessels called [[intervillous space]].<ref name=\"Wang Y & Zhao S\">   </ref>\n\nFocusing on oxygen exchange, there are 3 important aspects that allow it to pass from the maternal circulation into the fetal circulation. Firstly, the presence of hemoglobin F in the fetus allows a stronger binding to oxygen than maternal hemoglobin. Secondly, the mother\u2019s bloodstream is richer in oxygen that the fetus\u2019, so oxygen naturally flows towards the fetal circulation by diffusion.<ref name=\"Metcalfe1967\"> {{cite journal | authors=Metcalfe J, Bartels H and Moll W |title= Gas exchange in the pregnant uterus.  |journal= Physiological reviews |volume=47 |issue=4 |pages=782-838 |date=1967 |doi= 10.1152/physrev.1967.47.4.782 }} </ref> The final factor is related to the effects of pH on maternal and fetal hemoglobin. As the maternal blood acquires more carbon dioxide, it becomes more acidic and favours the release of oxygen by the maternal hemoglobin. At the same time, the decrease in carbon dioxide in fetal blood makes it more alkaline and favours the uptake of oxygen. This is called the Bohr effect or [[Haldane effect]], which also happens in the air exchange in the lungs.<ref name=\"Sarah2015\"> {{cite journal | authors=Griffiths S and Campbell J |title= Placental structure, function and drug transfer |journal= Continuing Education in Anaesthesia Critical Care & Pain |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=84-89 |date=2015 |doi= 10.1093/bjaceaccp/mku013}} </ref> All of these 3 factors are present simultaneously and cooperate to improve the fetus\u2019 access to oxygen.\n\n\n==Clinical significance==\n\n===Treatment of sickle-cell disease===\n[[Image:Sicklecells.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Increasing the body's production of fetal hemoglobin is used as a strategy to treat [[sickle-cell disease]].]]\n\n{{main article|Sickle-cell disease#Hydroxyurea}}\n\nWhen fetal hemoglobin production is switched off after birth, normal children begin producing adult hemoglobin (HbA). Children with [[sickle-cell disease]] instead begin producing a defective form of hemoglobin called [[hemoglobin S]] which aggregates together and forms filaments that cause [[red blood cell]]s to change their shape from round to [[sickle]]-shaped.<ref name=\u201dNIH_Sicklecelldisease\u201c> {{cite web |url= https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/sickle-cell-disease| title= Sickle cell disease| date= 2020-03-15|website= U.S. National Library of Medicine|publisher= NIH |access-date= 2020-03-15}} </ref>\n\nThese defective red blood cells have a greater tendency to form aggregates and block small [[blood vessel]]s, preventing blood supply ot tissues and organs. These invariably lead to so-called ''[[vaso-occlusive crisis]]'', which are a hallmark of the disease.<ref name=\" Deepa2013\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Manwani D and Frenette P|title= Vaso-occlusion in sickle cell disease: pathophysiology and novel targeted therapies|journal= Blood|volume= 122|pages= 3892-98|date= 2013|doi= 10.1182/blood-2013-05-498311}}</ref>\n\n\nIf fetal hemoglobin remains relatively high after birth, the number of painful episodes decreases in patients with sickle-cell disease and they have a better prognostic.<ref name=\" Idow2011\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Akinsheye I, Solovieff N Ngo D, Malek A, Sebastiani P, Steinberg M and Chui D|title= Fetal Hemoglobin in Sickle Cell Anemia: Molecular characterisation of the unusually high fetal hemoglobin phenotype in African Americans|journal= American Journal of Hematology|volume= 87|pages= 217-219|date= 2011|doi= 10.1002/ajh.22221}}</ref>\nFetal hemoglobin's role in reducing disease severity comes from its ability to disrupt the formation of hemoglobin S aggregates within red blood cells.<ref name=\"Ma2007\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Ma Q, Wyszynski D, Farrel J, Kutlar A, Farrer L, Baldwin C and Steinberg M|title= Fetal hemoglobin in sickle cell anaemia: genetic determinants of response of hydroxyurea|journal= The Pharmacogenomics Journal |volume= 7|pages= 386-394|date= 2007|doi= 10.1038/sj.tpj.6500433}}</ref> \n\n[[Hydroxyurea]] is a chemical that promotes the production of fetal hemoglobin and reduces the premature rupturing of red blood cells.<ref name=\"pmid18458272\"/><ref name=\"pmid7715639\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Charache S, Terrin ML, Moore RD, etal |title=Effect of hydroxyurea on the frequency of painful crises in sickle cell anemia. Investigators of the Multicenter Study of Hydroxyurea in Sickle Cell Anemia |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=332 |issue=20 |pages=1317\u201322 |date=May 1995 |pmid=7715639 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM199505183322001}}</ref> The fetal hemoglobin's reduction in the severity of the disease comes from its ability to inhibit the formation of hemoglobin aggregates within red blood cells which also contain hemoglobin S. Combination therapy with hydroxyurea and recombinant [[erythropoietin]]&mdash;rather than treatment with hydroxyurea alone&mdash;has been shown to further elevate hemoglobin F levels and to promote the development of HbF-containing F-cells.<ref name=\"pmid7677965\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Rodgers GP, Dover GJ, Uyesaka N, Noguchi CT, Schechter AN, Nienhuis AW |title=Augmentation by erythropoietin of the fetal-hemoglobin response to hydroxyurea in sickle cell disease |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=328 |issue=2 |pages=73\u201380 |date=January 1993 |pmid=7677965 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM199301143280201}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hemoglobinopathy.html Hemoglobinopathies]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040609153506/http://arbl.cvmbs.colostate.edu/hbooks/pathphys/reprod/placenta/transport.html Transport across the placenta]\n* [http://www.ascaa.org/ American Sickle Cell Anemia Association]\n* [http://www.sicklecelldisease.org SCDAA: Break The Sickle Cycle]\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hbsynthesis.html Hemoglobin synthesis]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020203114057/http://ntri.tamuk.edu/homepage-ntri/lectures/protein/hemoglobin/hempage.html Hemoglobin structure and function (archived February 3, 2002]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091029025455/http://fha.maryland.gov/genetics/hemo_f.cfm Hemoglobin F fact sheet (archived October 29, 2009)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20030330064928/http://www.isat.jmu.edu/users/klevicca/ISAT454/FetalHb.doc Fetal hemoglobin (doc file; archived March 30 2003)]\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hyguid.html Hydroxyurea in sickle-cell disease] (archived December 28, 2014 at [https://web.archive.org/web/20141228112837/http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hyguid.html])\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150329032048/http://scinfo.org/the-management-of-sickle-cell-disease-4th-ed/special-topics-chapter-26-fetal-hemoglobin-induction Chapter 26 Fetal Hemoglobin Induction; Management of Sickle-Cell Disease 4th Edition 2002 (NIH Publication No. 02-2117)]\n\n{{Globins}}\n\n[[Category:Hemoglobins]]\n[[Category:Infancy]]\n[[Category:Embryology of cardiovascular system]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox heteropolypeptide\n | heteropolymer = Fetal hemoglobin \n | polymer_type = 4 subunits, \u03b1<sub>2</sub>\u03b3<sub>2</sub>\n | protein_type = [[metalloprotein]], [[globulin]]\n | function = [[oxygen]]-transport\n | cofactors = [[heme]] (4)\n | image = Structure of Fetal Hemoglobin (HbF).png\n | image_source = Structure of Fetal Hemoglobin (HbF). The '''2\u03b1''' and '''2\u03b3''' subunits are in red and yellow, respectively, and the iron-containing [[heme]] groups in green. From {{PDB|4MQJ}}, by authors Soman, J. and Olson J.S.\n | SubunitCount = 4\n | subunit1 = Hb-\u03b11\n | gene1 = [[HBA1]]\n | locus1 = [[Chromosome 16|Chr. 16]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBA1#location?chromosome=16p13.3 p13.3]\n | subunit2 = Hb-\u03b12\n | gene2 = [[HBA2]]\n | locus2 = [[Chromosome 16|Chr. 16]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBA2#location?chromosome=16p13.3 p13.3]\n | subunit3 = Hb-\u03b31\n | gene3 = [[HBG1]]\n | locus3 = [[Chromosome 11|Chr. 11]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG1#location?chromosome=11p15.4 p15.4]\n | subunit4 = Hb-\u03b32\n | gene4 = [[HBG2]]\n | locus4 = [[Chromosome 11|Chr. 11]] [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG2#location?chromosome=11p15.4 p15.4]\n}}\n\n'''Fetal hemoglobin''', or '''foetal haemoglobin''' (also '''hemoglobin F''', '''HbF''', or '''\u03b1<sub>2</sub>\u03b3<sub>2</sub>''') is the main [[oxygen]] [[transport protein|carrier protein]] in the human [[fetus]]. Hemoglobin F is found in fetal red blood cells and it is involved in transporting oxygen from the mother's [[bloodstream]] to organs and tissues in the fetus. It is produced at around 6 weeks of pregnancy <ref name=\"David 1998\">{{cite book |last= Linch|first= David|date= 1998|title= Encyclopedia of Immunology (second edition)|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B0122267656001031 |publisher= Elsevier|isbn= 978-0-12-226765-9}}</ref> and the levels remain high after birth until the baby is roughly 2-4 months old.<ref name=\"Schechter2008\">{{Cite journal | author=Schechter A | title=Hemoglobin research and the origins of molecular medicine | journal=[[Blood]] | volume=112(10) | year=2008 | pages=3927\u20133938 | doi=10.1182/blood-2008-04-078188 }}</ref> Hemoglobin F has a different composition from the adult forms of [[hemoglobin]], which allows it to bind (or attach to) oxygen more strongly. This way, the developing fetus is able to retrieve oxygen from the mother's bloodstream, which occurs through the [[placenta]] found in the mother\u2019s [[uterus]].<ref name=\"Wang Y & Zhao S\">{{Cite book | authors= Wang Y, Zhao S| title= Vascular Biology of the Placenta| year=2010 | chapter=Chapter 2: Placental Blood Circulation | publisher=Morgan & Claypool Life Sciences }}</ref>\n\n\nIn the newborn, levels of hemoglobin F gradually decrease and reach adult levels (less than 1% of total hemoglobin) usually within 1 year of life, as adult forms of hemoglobin begin to be produced.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\">{{cite book |last= Wild|first= Barbara|date= 2017|title= Dacie and Lewis Practical Haematology (twelfth edition)|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B978070206696200014X |publisher= Elsevier|isbn= 978-0-7020-6696-2}}</ref> Diseases such as [[\u03b2-thalassemia]], which affect components of the adult hemoglobin, can delay this switch and cause hemoglobin F levels to be higher than normal in these patients.<ref name=\"Orapan2016\">{{Cite journal | author=Orapan S & Suthat F| title=Fetal hemoglobin regulation in \u03b2-thalassemia: heterogeneity, modifiers and therapeutic approaches | journal=[[Expert review of hematology]] | volume=9(12) |year=2016 | pages=1129\u20131137 | doi=10.1080/17474086.2016.1255142 }}</ref> In sickle cell anaemia, increasing the production of hemoglobin F has been used as a treatment, as it relieves some of the symptoms of the disease.<ref name=\"pmid18458272\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Lanzkron S, Strouse JJ, Wilson R, etal |title=Systematic review: Hydroxyurea for the treatment of adults with sickle cell disease |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |volume=148 |issue=12 |pages=939\u201355 |date=June 2008 |pmid=18458272 |doi= 10.7326/0003-4819-148-12-200806170-00221|url= |pmc=3256736}}</ref>\n\n\n==Structure and genetics==\nHemoglobin F, like hemoglobin forms found in adults ([[hemoglobin A]] and [[hemoglobin A2]]), have four [[protein subunit|subunits]] or chains. Each subunit contains a [[heme]] group with an iron element which is key in allowing the binding and unbinding of oxygen. As hemoglobin F has 4 heme groups, it can bind to up to four oxygen molecules.<ref name=brsphys>{{cite book |author=Costanzo, Linda S. |title=Physiology |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location=Hagerstwon, MD |year=2007 |isbn=978-0781773119 |url=https://archive.org/details/physiology00cost_0 }}</ref> Fetal hemoglobin is composed of '''two \u03b1 (alpha)''' subunits and '''two \u03b3 (gamma)''' subunits, whereas hemoglobin A (97% of total hemoglobin in adults) is composed of two \u03b1 and two \u03b2 (beta) subunits.\n\nIn humans, the \u03b1 subunit is encoded on [[chromosome 16 (human)|chromosome 16]] and the \u03b3 subunit is encoded on [[chromosome 11 (human)|chromosome 11]]. There are 2 very similar [[gene]]s that code for the \u03b1 subunit, [[HBA1]] and [[HBA2]]. The protein that they produce is identical, but they differ in gene regulatory regions that determine when or how much of the protein is produced. This leads to HBA1 and HBA2 each contributing with 40% and 60%, respectively, of the total of \u03b1 subunits produced. As a consequence, mutations on the HBA2 gene are expected to have a stronger effect than mutations on the HBA1 gene.<ref name=\"Samaneh2018\">{{Cite journal | author=Samaneh F & Cornelis L| title=Molecular basis of \u03b1-thalassemia | journal=[[Blood cells, Molecules and Diseases]] | volume=70 |year=2018 | pages=43\u201353 | doi=10.1016/j.bcmd.2017.09.004 }}</ref> \nThere are also two similar copies of the gene coding for the \u03b3 subunit, HBG1 and HBG2, but the protein produced is slightly different, just in one [[amino acid|protein unit]]: HBG1 codes for the protein form with an [[alanine]] at position 136, whereas HBG2 codes for a [[glycine]] (see [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/HBG1|NIH]).\n\n==When hemoglobin F is produced==\n[[File:Postnatal genetics en.svg|thumb|300px|[[Gene expression]] of hemoglobin before and after birth, also showing the cells types and organs where different subunits are being produced over time (data on ''Wood W.G.'', (1976). '''Br. Med. Bull. 32, 282.''') Figure last adapted by user Leonid 2.]]\n\nDuring the first 3 months of pregnancy, the main form of hemoglobin in the fetus is [[embryonic hemoglobin]], which has 3 variants. The production of fetal hemoglobin starts from week 6, but it's only from 3 months onwards that it becomes the main type found in red blood cells.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\"/>\nThe switch to produce adult forms of hemoglobin (especially Hemoglobin A) starts at around 40 weeks of gestation, which is close to the expected time of birth.<ref name=\"David 1998\"/> At birth, hemoglobin F comprises 50-95% of the infant's hemoglobin and at around 6 months after birth, hemoglobin A becomes the predominant type. By the time the baby is one year old, the proportions of different types of hemoglobin are expected to approximate the adult levels.<ref name=\"Barbara2017\" />\n\nIn healthy adults, the composition of hemoglobin is hemoglobin A (~97%), hemoglobin A2 (2.2 - 3.5%) and hemoglobin F (<1%).<ref name=\"Caroline 2012\">{{Cite journal | author=Caroline T & Andrew L| title= Physiology of haemoglobin| journal=[[Continuing Education in Anaesthesia Critical Care & Pain]] | volume=12(5) |year=2012 | pages=251\u2013256 | doi=10.1093/bjaceaccp/mks025 }}</ref>\n\nCertain genetic abnormalities can cause the switch to adult hemoglobin synthesis to fail, resulting in a condition known as [[hereditary persistence of fetal hemoglobin]] (HPFH).\n\n\n\n==Binding to oxygen==\n===Why hemoglobin F has higher oxygen affinity===\nThe 4 hemes, which are the oxygen-binding parts of hemoglobin, are similar between hemoglobin F and other types of hemoglobin, including hemoglobin A. Thus, the key feature that allows hemoglobin F to bind more strongly to oxygen is by having \u03b3 subunits (instead of \u03b2, for example). In fact, some naturally existing molecules in our body can bind to hemoglobin and change its binding affinity for oxygen. One of the molecules is [[2,3-bisphosphoglycerate|2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG)]] and it enhances hemoglobin\u2019s ability to release oxygen.<ref name=\"Gerald 2018\">  {{Cite book | authors= Litwack G| title= Human Biochemistry | year=2018 | chapter=Chapter 8 \u2013 Glycolysis and Glocuneogenesis | publisher=Academic press| isbn = 978-0-12-383864-3}} </ref> 2,3-BPG interacts much more with hemoglobin A than hemoglobin F. This is because the adult \u03b2 subunit has more positive charges than the fetal \u03b3 subunit, which attract the negative charges from 2,3-BPG. Due to the preference of 2,3-BPG for hemoglobin A, hemoglobin F binds to oxygen with more affinity, in average.<ref name=\"Duane 2016\"> {{cite web |url=https://biosci.mcdb.ucsb.edu/biochemistry/tw-hbn/hbf/hbf-overview.htm\n|title= Comparing the molecular structure differences between HbF and HbA that affect BPG binding|last= Sears|first= Duane|date= 2016|website= https://biosci.mcdb.ucsb.edu/|publisher= Biosci Portal |access-date= 11 March 2020}} </ref>\n\n===Quantification of oxygen binding=== \nTo quantify how strongly a certain type of hemoglobin binds to oxygen (or its affinity for oxygen), a parameter called P50 is often used. In a given situation, P50 can be understood as the minimum concentration of oxygen needed for 50% of the hemoglobin molecules to bind to it.<ref name=\"Vibhu2006\">  {{Cite book | authors= Awasthi V, Goins E and Phillips W| title= Blood Substitutes| year=2006 | chapter=Chapter 43 \u2013 Liposome-encapsulated hemoglobin: history, preparation and evaluation | publisher=Academic press| isbn = 978-0-12-759760-7}} </ref> For example, Hemoglobin F has a lower P50 than hemoglobin A. This means that if we have the same amount of hemoglobin F and hemoglobin A in the blood and add oxygen to it, half of hemoglobin F will bind to oxygen before half of hemoglobin A manages to do so. Therefore, a lower P50 means stronger binding or higher affinity for oxygen. \n\nFor reference, the P50 of fetal hemoglobin is roughly 19 mmHg (a measure of pressure), whereas adult hemoglobin is approximately 26.8 mmHg (see [[Blood gas tension]]).<ref name=\"Yacov2017\">  {{Cite book | authors= Yacov R, Derek K and Namasivayam A| title= Assisted Ventilation of the Neonate (sixth edition)| year=2017 | chapter=Chapter 10 \u2013 Blood gases: technical aspects and interpretation | publisher=Elsevier| isbn = 978-0-323-39006-4 }} </ref>\n\n\n==Oxygen exchange in the womb==\nDuring pregnancy, the mother\u2019s circulatory system delivers oxygen and nutrients to the fetus and carries away nutrient-depleted blood enriched with carbon dioxide. The maternal and fetal-placental circulation are separate and the exchange of molecules occurs in a region between maternal and fetal blood vessels called [[intervillous space]].<ref name=\"Wang Y & Zhao S\">   </ref>\n\nFocusing on oxygen exchange, there are 3 important aspects that allow it to pass from the maternal circulation into the fetal circulation. Firstly, the presence of hemoglobin F in the fetus allows a stronger binding to oxygen than maternal hemoglobin. Secondly, the mother\u2019s bloodstream is richer in oxygen that the fetus\u2019, so oxygen naturally flows towards the fetal circulation by diffusion.<ref name=\"Metcalfe1967\"> {{cite journal | authors=Metcalfe J, Bartels H and Moll W |title= Gas exchange in the pregnant uterus.  |journal= Physiological reviews |volume=47 |issue=4 |pages=782-838 |date=1967 |doi= 10.1152/physrev.1967.47.4.782 }} </ref> The final factor is related to the effects of pH on maternal and fetal hemoglobin. As the maternal blood acquires more carbon dioxide, it becomes more acidic and favours the release of oxygen by the maternal hemoglobin. At the same time, the decrease in carbon dioxide in fetal blood makes it more alkaline and favours the uptake of oxygen. This is called the Bohr effect or [[Haldane effect]], which also happens in the air exchange in the lungs.<ref name=\"Sarah2015\"> {{cite journal | authors=Griffiths S and Campbell J |title= Placental structure, function and drug transfer |journal= Continuing Education in Anaesthesia Critical Care & Pain |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=84-89 |date=2015 |doi= 10.1093/bjaceaccp/mku013}} </ref> All of these 3 factors are present simultaneously and cooperate to improve the fetus\u2019 access to oxygen.\n\n\n==Clinical significance==\n\n===Treatment of sickle-cell disease===\n[[Image:Sicklecells.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Increasing the body's production of fetal hemoglobin is used as a strategy to treat [[sickle-cell disease]].]]\n\n{{main article|Sickle-cell disease#Hydroxyurea}}\n\nWhen fetal hemoglobin production is switched off after birth, normal children begin producing adult hemoglobin (HbA). Children with [[sickle-cell disease]] instead begin producing a defective form of hemoglobin called [[hemoglobin S]] which aggregates together and forms filaments that cause [[red blood cell]]s to change their shape from round to [[sickle]]-shaped.<ref name=\u201dNIH_Sicklecelldisease\u201c> {{cite web |url= https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/sickle-cell-disease| title= Sickle cell disease| date= 2020-03-15|website= U.S. National Library of Medicine|publisher= NIH |access-date= 2020-03-15}} </ref>\n\nThese defective red blood cells have a greater tendency to form aggregates and block small [[blood vessel]]s, preventing blood supply ot tissues and organs. These invariably lead to so-called ''[[vaso-occlusive crisis]]'', which are a hallmark of the disease.<ref name=\" Deepa2013\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Manwani D and Frenette P|title= Vaso-occlusion in sickle cell disease: pathophysiology and novel targeted therapies|journal= Blood|volume= 122|pages= 3892-98|date= 2013|doi= 10.1182/blood-2013-05-498311}}</ref>\n\n\nIf fetal hemoglobin remains relatively high after birth, the number of painful episodes decreases in patients with sickle-cell disease and they have a better prognostic.<ref name=\" Idow2011\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Akinsheye I, Solovieff N Ngo D, Malek A, Sebastiani P, Steinberg M and Chui D|title= Fetal Hemoglobin in Sickle Cell Anemia: Molecular characterisation of the unusually high fetal hemoglobin phenotype in African Americans|journal= American Journal of Hematology|volume= 87|pages= 217-219|date= 2011|doi= 10.1002/ajh.22221}}</ref>\nFetal hemoglobin's role in reducing disease severity comes from its ability to disrupt the formation of hemoglobin S aggregates within red blood cells.<ref name=\"Ma2007\"> {{cite journal  | authors= Ma Q, Wyszynski D, Farrel J, Kutlar A, Farrer L, Baldwin C and Steinberg M|title= Fetal hemoglobin in sickle cell anaemia: genetic determinants of response of hydroxyurea|journal= The Pharmacogenomics Journal |volume= 7|pages= 386-394|date= 2007|doi= 10.1038/sj.tpj.6500433}}</ref> \n\n[[Hydroxyurea]] is a chemical that promotes the production of fetal hemoglobin and reduces the premature rupturing of red blood cells.<ref name=\"pmid18458272\"/><ref name=\"pmid7715639\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Charache S, Terrin ML, Moore RD, etal |title=Effect of hydroxyurea on the frequency of painful crises in sickle cell anemia. Investigators of the Multicenter Study of Hydroxyurea in Sickle Cell Anemia |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=332 |issue=20 |pages=1317\u201322 |date=May 1995 |pmid=7715639 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM199505183322001}}</ref> The fetal hemoglobin's reduction in the severity of the disease comes from its ability to inhibit the formation of hemoglobin aggregates within red blood cells which also contain hemoglobin S. Combination therapy with hydroxyurea and recombinant [[erythropoietin]]&mdash;rather than treatment with hydroxyurea alone&mdash;has been shown to further elevate hemoglobin F levels and to promote the development of HbF-containing F-cells.<ref name=\"pmid7677965\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Rodgers GP, Dover GJ, Uyesaka N, Noguchi CT, Schechter AN, Nienhuis AW |title=Augmentation by erythropoietin of the fetal-hemoglobin response to hydroxyurea in sickle cell disease |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=328 |issue=2 |pages=73\u201380 |date=January 1993 |pmid=7677965 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM199301143280201}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hemoglobinopathy.html Hemoglobinopathies]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040609153506/http://arbl.cvmbs.colostate.edu/hbooks/pathphys/reprod/placenta/transport.html Transport across the placenta]\n* [http://www.ascaa.org/ American Sickle Cell Anemia Association]\n* [http://www.sicklecelldisease.org SCDAA: Break The Sickle Cycle]\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hbsynthesis.html Hemoglobin synthesis]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020203114057/http://ntri.tamuk.edu/homepage-ntri/lectures/protein/hemoglobin/hempage.html Hemoglobin structure and function (archived February 3, 2002]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091029025455/http://fha.maryland.gov/genetics/hemo_f.cfm Hemoglobin F fact sheet (archived October 29, 2009)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20030330064928/http://www.isat.jmu.edu/users/klevicca/ISAT454/FetalHb.doc Fetal hemoglobin (doc file; archived March 30 2003)]\n* [http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hyguid.html Hydroxyurea in sickle-cell disease] (archived December 28, 2014 at [https://web.archive.org/web/20141228112837/http://sickle.bwh.harvard.edu/hyguid.html])\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150329032048/http://scinfo.org/the-management-of-sickle-cell-disease-4th-ed/special-topics-chapter-26-fetal-hemoglobin-induction Chapter 26 Fetal Hemoglobin Induction; Management of Sickle-Cell Disease 4th Edition 2002 (NIH Publication No. 02-2117)]\n\n{{Globins}}\n\n[[Category:Hemoglobins]]\n[[Category:Infancy]]\n[[Category:Embryology of cardiovascular system]]\n", "name_user": "Sciencingabout", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStructure and genetics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fetal_hemoglobin"}
